<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>Java on My Workbook</title><link>https://ashishdoneriya.github.io/topics/java/</link><description>Recent content in Java on My Workbook</description><generator>Hugo</generator><language>en</language><lastBuildDate>Sun, 22 Jun 2025 10:00:00 +0530</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="https://ashishdoneriya.github.io/topics/java/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>Build Spring Boot JAR Without Local Java Using Docker</title><link>https://ashishdoneriya.github.io/build-spring-boot-jar-with-docker-no-java.html</link><pubDate>Sun, 22 Jun 2025 10:00:00 +0530</pubDate><guid>https://ashishdoneriya.github.io/build-spring-boot-jar-with-docker-no-java.html</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;If you’re working on a Spring Boot project that targets Java 17, 21, or 24, but your system only has Java 8 (or no Java at all), building the .jar with mvn clean install becomes impossible.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id="the-problem-we-want-to"&gt;The Problem: We want to&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Build the Spring Boot .jar using Docker (no local Java or Maven)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Extract only the built .jar to our host system&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Clean up the container, image, and temporary Dockerfile&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Avoid polluting the final image with source code&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;h2 id="the-solution-a-simple-bash-script"&gt;The Solution: A Simple Bash Script&lt;/h2&gt;
